 did revenant stories and imagery take such a hold in the Middle Ages? And why has that fascination held on into today's world? This book offers a history ofthese revenant narratives, demonstrating how modern horror is haunted by past literature and exploring the motif of the risen dead as a focus of cultural anxiety and literary effort. The author examines the long arc of revenant tales from antiquity and the Middle Ages through the Reformation and into modernity, tracing their uncanny similarities and laying bare the rich traditions of narrative, theme, motif, supernatural belief and eschatological fears and preoccupations. CHRISTIAN LIVERMORE gained her PhD in medieval English literature and creative writing from the University of St Andrews.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDeadvFolklore. 0aDeadxReligious aspects. 0aDeathxSymbolic aspects. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aLegend Myth & Folklore. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAwyntyrs off Arthure.  aDance of Death.  aFrancis Child.  aGhosts.  aJohn Lydgate.  aThree Living and Three Dead.  aWife of Usher's Well.  aballads.  arevenants.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311143100040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781800101418?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781800101418423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781800101418/original  a978-3-11-143100-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles